data.content:
Three things break. Here's each one with the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire expression-tree construction is no longer needed. Replace with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

The `Action`-based overload lets you use normal C# control flow — no more `Expression.Lambda`/`Expression.Call` machinery.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Duplicate property names are now uniquified.** Since both `ShippingAddress` and `BillingAddress` have a `Street` property, EF 10 appends a number to disambiguate (e.g., `Street1`). Pin the old names:

```csharp
b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, a => {
    a.Property(x => x.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
});
b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, a => {
    a.Property(x => x.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now include the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was mapped to `BillingAddress_City` — it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To keep the old name:

```csharp
b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p => {
    p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, a => {
        a.Property(x => x.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
    });
});
```

Without explicit `HasColumnName()`, a migration will be generated that renames these columns.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface now has an additional `string logCommandText` parameter. Add it:

```csharp
public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
    IRelationalConnection connection, DbCommand command,
    DbContext context, Guid commandId, Guid connectionId,
    DateTimeOffset startTime,
    string logCommandText)          // ← new parameter (redacted SQL)
{ /* logging — use logCommandText for safe log output */ }
```

Update all implemented methods from the interface the same way, or this won't compile.
